<F P=100> AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Arrest Man Involved in Drug `Syndicate' Near Durban </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2601164694 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1400 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2601164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Durban Jan 26 SAPA -- A 45-year-old electrician was 
arrested in Amanzimtoti near Durban on Tuesday with about 150 kg 
of dagga [marijuana] apparently destined for The Netherlands. 
Police spokesman Maj Bala Naidoo said on Wednesday the dagga 
was compressed in 127 packages hidden in two pool tables. Its 
South African street value was about R[rand]150,000, but it 
would have fetched R4 million in The Netherlands. 
  Durban Narcotics Chief Maj Piet Meyer said Tuesday's arrest 
was part of an investigation into a drug syndicate. The same 
people had been implicated in about five similar cases in the 
past three years. "We are still busy with further investigations 
to see if we can close down the syndicate once and for all," Maj 
Meyer said, adding that the organisers preyed on unsuspecting 
people, manipulating them into doing the "dirty work" for a 
portion of the profit. 
  He said South Africa's superior quality dagga was much 
sought 
after overseas. Amsterdam's got most of its dagga from South 
Africa and Morocco, but "South African dagga is more potent and 
it's in demand because the quality is better," Maj Meyer said. 
  The man is expected to appear in court this week. 

</TEXT>

