<F P=100> EAST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruml Fears Drug-Related Crime May Reach `European Proportions' Soon </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0402170594 Prague CTK in English 1253 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0402170594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Strasbourg, Prague Feb 4 (CTK) -- Drug-related 
crime in the Czech Republic might soon reach "European 
proportions," in spite of international cooperation in the 
struggle against it, Czech Interior Minister Jan Ruml told the 
2nd international conference on struggle against drug abuse 
today. 
  "I admit that I am really afraid of the future. This stems 
from the fact that a great number of UN conventions have been in 
force for thirty years, but the drug-related crime has not 
decreased, rather the contrary. I am concerned by the statement 
of director-general of the Interpol that the struggle against 
illegal drug trafficking has failed and legalisation of drugs is 
a possible solution for the future," Ruml noted. 
  He described his election as deputy chairman of the 
conference as an expression of the Czech Republic's effort to 
contribute to the struggle against the drug danger, Ruml said. 
  The conference was staged by the expert organisation for 
cooperation of the struggle against drug abuse and drug 
trafficking within the European Council which is known as the 
Pompidou Group. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

