<F P=100> WEST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> ITALY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Milan Police Seize 100 Kg of Heroin; One Person Arrested </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0402114694 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1917 GMT 4 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BR0402114694 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Police Seize 100k of Heroin"] </F>
  [Text] Milan, 3 Feb (ANSA) -- Milan police today seized one 
quintal [100 kg] of pure heroin with a street value of close to 
five million dollars and arrested a suspected 'Ndrangheta 
organized crime figure to conclude an operation which began over 
the year-end holiday period when the automobile owned by the 
alleged courier was secretly fitted with an electronic tracking 
device. 
  Police here, who worked with the Criminalpol branch and the 
special narcotics squad, said Vincenzo Mobilio, 38, was stopped 
today at a toll booth east of Milan leading off the Venice-Milan 
expressway where they found 100k [kg] of uncut heroin in the 
boot of his car. He had been under close surveillance since 
Tuesday afternoon [1 February] when he left Milan for Venice. 
  The suspect is from a town in the southern Calabria region 
and now lives in Milan with his wife and three children. He is 
thought by investigators to be on the payroll of the 
Calabria-based 'Ndrangheta. 
  A police spokesman said the heroin had been "professionally 
packaged" in one-kilogram insulated bags "with a technique of 
great precision, something new for us." The goods could have 
been cut seven times, seven kilograms for retailing for each 
kilogram of the Turkish-produced drug. 
  Milan Police Chief Achille Serra reported that the haul was 
the biggest since November 1985 when a shipment of 114k [kg] was 
seized here. He also explained that the wholesale price of this 
type of heroin has doubled over the past year, to nearly 50,000 
dollars per kilogram, because traffickers have been experiencing 
increasing difficulty in laying hands on the Turkish goods. 

</TEXT>

