<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> LITHUANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Signing of UN Conventions Will Make Antidrug Battle `More Efficient' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0102200694 Tallinn BNS in English 1632 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0102200694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Feb 01, BNS -- Lithuania has joined the 
1961 U.N. convention on narcotic substances and the 1971 U.N. 
convention on psychotropic substances. 
  Although no specfic information is available, experts 
suppose 
that the Baltic states have become a new transit point for drugs 
smuggled to the West. 
  Ona Grimalauskiene, consultant at the Lithuanian Ministry of 
Health Care, said the step will make the struggle against drug 
abuse and drug transit through Lithuanian territory more 
efficient. The above conventions not only oblige Lithuania to 
observe international drug control standards, but also offer 
technical assistance to Lithuanian customs, police and doctors, 
she said. Lithuania can expect help in this field from both 
international organizations and European countries. 
  The Lithuanian Government intends to create a National Drug 
Control Committee that will coordinate the country's drug 
control policy. Drug abuse prophylaxis will be one of the 
committee's principal fields of activity. 
  According to a Jan. 27 government resolution, antidrug laws 
will be drafted in accordance with the two conventions by next 
fall. 

</TEXT>

