<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chile, Bolivia Agree To Boost Cooperative Antinarcotics Efforts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0702120394 Santiago Radio Cooperativa Network in Spanish 
1000 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0702120394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santiago Radio Cooperativa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] During a meeting in La Paz, Bolivia, to discuss the 
struggle against drug trafficking, Chilean and Bolivian 
government representatives agreed to exchange information on 
juridical affairs, customs, drug trafficking and the prevention 
of drug abuse, and social rehabilitation programs. 
  Gustavo Villalobos, secretary of the Chilean National 
Council 
for Drug Control, noted that the level of cooperation between 
the two countries is very high even though they do not maintain 
diplomatic relations. 
  Villalobos added that the bilateral cooperation efforts to 
fight trafficking also benefit other countries of the region. 
  Bolivian Social Defense Secretary Marcos Solis said the 
struggle against trafficking requires considerable international 
solidarity. 
  The two countries agreed to exchange judicial resolutions 
and 
letters rogatory. [sentence as received] The representatives 
also discussed the possibility of extraditing traffickers. 

</TEXT>

