<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> COLOMBIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Medellin Cartel Members Offer Deal to Pepes Organization </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0602212494 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1739 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0602212494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 6 Feb (NOTIMEX) -- The military 
chiefs of the weakened Medellin Cartel in Colombia are willing 
to negotiate a peace agreement with the enemies of that dreadful 
organization to prevent their total extermination, the local 
press revealed today. 
  According to EL TIEMPO, during the past 70 days the 
survivors 
of the Medellin Cartel who are currently in jail have 
unsuccessfully sent letters to their emissaries in Cali, the 
country's third largest city, seeking a peace agreement with the 
Mafia in that region. 
  Some time ago, the clandestine group "Pepes" [Persecuted by 
Pablo Escobar], reportedly made up of members of the Cali 
Cartel, announced it would reactivate its struggle against the 
men of slain drug trafficker Pablo Escobar until all the members 
of the once powerful organization are exterminated. 
  "Afraid of what could happen to them--after Escobar's 
death--the terrorist chiefs of the Medellin Cartel have offered 
to pay their debts in jail and for the first time have 
considered the possibility of dismantling whatever is left of 
their armed redoubts," the newspaper said. "In exchange, they 
have requested respect for their relatives' lives and 
negotiations for their money and properties," with Pablo 
Escobar's widow Maria Victoria Henao. 
  Since its creation a year ago, "Pepes" has killed more than 
50 of Pablo Escobar's men and destroyed some 30 properties 
belonging to the Medellin Cartel. According to the police, the 
hunt for the survivors of the Medellin Cartel who are free has 
continued after Escobar's death and this is keeping the people 
related to this organization in a state of fear. The source 
said that "the authorities have evidence related to the killing 
of several cartel agents in Medellin one week ago." 
  One of Escobar's trusted men has said: "Either we kneel or 
they kill us all." This man has confirmed that the terrorist 
chiefs of the cartel are making efforts to secure a peace 
agreement with their enemies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-41221 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptdd007__l94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TDD-94-007-L </AU>
Document Type:JPRS 
Document Title:Narcotics 

<DATE1>  14 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> COLOMBIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report Sketches Main Objectives of New U.S. Drug Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1102021994 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1102021994 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President Bill Clinton has finally announced his 
counternarcotics policy. He will step up the fight against drug 
consumption in the United States and will give more economic 
support to eradication and substitution of drug cultivation in 
drug-producing countries. Miriam Ortiz has the report on what 
that program means for Colombia. 
  [Begin recording] [Ortiz] President Bill Clinton's new 
counternarcotics program has four fundamental objectives. The 
first is to reduce demand. This is the most important goal of 
the new strategy. Budgets for prevention, treatment, and 
education programs will be increased. The second objective is 
to reduce drug-related violence. The U.S. Government will 
appoint 100 policemen [as heard] to prevent crime in the streets 
and will ask Congress to pass more controls and requirements on 
gun ownership. The third objective is to reject the 
legalization and decriminalization of illegal drugs. The fourth 
is to request international cooperation. 
  According to the drug czar [Lee Brown], the U.S. Government 
will continue to be a strong ally of countries that have 
demonstrated a political willingness to fight drug trafficking. 
  [Brown, in English with superimposed translation into 
Spanish] It's very important that we do not open our borders to 
the Escobars of the world to bring drugs in at will. That is 
why we will continue our program to ban drugs. 
  [Ortiz] The U.S. Government believes that Colombia has one 
of 
the most successful counternarcotics programs, so its budget 
will not be reduced. 
  [Gabriel Silva, Colombian ambassador to Washington] In 
addition to support for efforts to reduce consumption, the new 
program includes institutional support, which will strengthen 
justice and democratic institutions. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

