<F P=101> CUBA </F>
<H3> <TI>   2.5 Tons of `Lost' Cocaine Incinerated During 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0802151894 Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks in 
Spanish 0100 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0802151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bags of cocaine that washed up on the coasts of 
Villa Clara, Ciego de Avila, Camaguey, and Guantanamo were 
incinerated by Ministry of the Interior workers and troops in 
the ovens of large industries of the country during 1993. We are 
referring to drugs that international traffickers lost during 
operations close to the territorial waters of Cuba. As on other 
occasions, members of the National Antidrug Commission, the 
Ministry of the Interior, and a representative of the Public 
Prosecutor's Office performed the analysis and certified the 
incineration of the 2.5 tons of cocaine that washed up on our 
coasts. This act affirms that Cuba's policy of confronting the 
actions of international drug trafficking remains unchanged. 

</TEXT>

