<F P=100> EAST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report Highlights 1993 Drug Seizures, Arrests </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002204994 Prague LIDOVE NOVINY in Czech 9 Feb 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> AU1002204994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague LIDOVE NOVINY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["(hop)"-signed report: "Drugs Are Mainly Smuggled Across </F>
the Czech Republic"] 
  [Text] Prague -- "The Czech Republic is far behind 
advanced Western countries in drug use," declared Interior 
Minister Jan Ruml. "Nevertheless, we rank among the countries 
across which narcotic substances are smuggled. At the same 
time, I do not deny that, to a certain extent, we are also one 
of the target and production countries but certainly not to the 
same extent as Western European states. It is our duty to 
prevent a drug environment being created in our country." 
  This was the interior minister's reaction to the recent 
statement by Council of Europe Secretary General Catherine 
Lalumiere that the countries of Central and Eastern Europe 
provide a suitable setting for the activities of various 
narcotics mafias. 
  According to our information, 18.5 kilograms of heroin, just 
under 5.0 kilograms of cocaine, 3.0 kilograms of morphine, 7.0 
kilograms of hashish, and 7.0 kilograms of amphetamines were 
seized in our country last year. Some 149 Czech citizens and 21 
foreign nationals were arrested for producing, smuggling, and 
distributing narcotic and psychotropic substances. Operation 
Bumerang, directed against pervitin producers in the capital and 
in the Kladno region, was one of the most successful police 
interventions in 1993. 
  Some 31 Czech citizens were investigated abroad last year 
for 
drug smuggling. The largest haul--47 kilograms of heroin--was 
found on a Czech citizen in Amsterdam in May. Two Czech drug 
traffickers, who tried to smuggle high-quality Asian heroin from 
Turkey to Western Europe last year, are now awaiting trial in a 
Bulgarian prison. The payment for such a risky journey is 
between $10,000 and $20,000. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

