<F P=100> WEST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Antinarcotics Operations for 4-9 February </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1002022594 </F>
<F P=103> LD1002022594 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
fileworthy reports on antinarcotics operations in countries 
covered by FBIS London Bureau from 4-9 February. Sources are 
given at the end of each report. 
<H5>  Germany </H5>
  On 26 January, customs officers found 90 kilos of heroin, 
worth 9 million German marks, in a Turkish truck crossing the 
German-Czech border at Furth im Wald. According to a press 
release from the Higher Tax Office in Nuremberg, the drugs were 
in transit to the Netherlands. (Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1307 
GMT 8 Feb 94) 
<H5>  Italy </H5>
  Fifteen people were arrested in Milan as part of an 
anti-drug 
operation. Officers seized 16.5 kg of heroin, 2 kg of cocaine, 
and 400 million lire in cash. The operation, code-named "Felix" 
after the leader of the gang, was carried out by officers from 
the Porta Genova police station with the help of Criminalpol, 
the flying squad, and the Central Anti-Drugs Directorate. (Rome 
RAI Televideo Teletext in Italian 0852 GMT 8 Feb 94) 
  Seven people, almost of all them foreign nationals living in 
Perugia, were arrested during an anti-drugs operation in which 
police seized seven kilograms of cocaine. The operation was 
coordinated by the Interior Ministry. (Rome RAI Televideo 
Teletext in Italian 0910 GMT 9 Feb 94) 
<H5>  United Kingdom </H5>
  Customs officers seized 1.3 tonnes of herbal cannabis with a 
street value of 3 million pounds from a Dutch truck arriving at 
Dover. The driver ran off while the truck was being searched. 
(London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1914 GMT 7 Feb 94) 

</TEXT>

