<H3> <TI>   Bolivian Cocaine Ring Disbanded in Porto Alegre </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WD0191C Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 11 
Jan 94 p 8--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94WD0191C </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] After 45 days of investigation, the Civil Police 
Drugs and Narcotics Headquarters in Rio Grande do Sul State have 
broken up a ring of cocaine traffickers from Bolivia. The 
ringleader was Odamir Davi Bertuol, 28, an engineer and owner of 
the Edifa condominium management company in Porto Alegre. His 
office was used as a narcotics contact and sales point. Two 
kilograms of cocaine were seized when the five people were 
arrested. 
  Every 15 days the group brought in 10 kilos of cocaine, 
reaping a $30,000 profit on each shipment. Chief Mauricio 
Finkelstein, of the narcotics headquarters, requested and 
obtained an order for temporary detention of those involved. 
They include Almeida Faviero dos Santos and Marcos Barcelos de 
Menezes--the latter worked three years at a secret 
cocaine-refining laboratory in the Bolivian jungle. 

</TEXT>

