<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> COLOMBIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   De Greiff Reportedly Negotiating With Cali Cartel `On His Own' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1402221394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1402221394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] The magazine SEMANA disclosed today that Prosecutor 
General Gustavo de Greiff, acting on his own and without 
consulting anyone, has been conducting negotiations for more 
than a month with members of the Cali Cartel. According to the 
publication, the document signed by De Greiff himself reportedly 
gave a kind of safe-conduct pass to alleged Cali and Tulua drug 
traffickers to keep them from being arrested in the future. The 
names of these drug traffickers are well-known figure Pacho 
Herrera, Jose Olmedo Campo, and a man named Renteria. According 
to the magazine, the passes would clearly show Prosecutor De 
Greiff has been in direct contact with the Cali Cartel 
chieftains for more than a month, without previously consulting 
the government or informing the security corps or the Attorney 
General's Office. SEMANA said a top government source expressed 
the government's surprise about the actions taken individually 
and privately by the prosecutor, since late last year the 
government and this office agreed to keep each other informed of 
any developments. 
  According to SEMANA, the serious thing about the case is not 
the fact that the prosecutor is acting like a loose cannon, but 
that from the moment when the drug traffickers first went to his 
office--that is on 14 January--it marked the beginning of the 
preliminary investigations. In other words, this marked the 
beginning of the search for evidence that must be provided by 
the DAS [Administrative Department of Security], the Dijin 
[Judicial Police and Investigations Directorate] in Colombia, 
and Interpol. The odd thing is that the Prosecutor General's 
Office did not officially inform any of these organizations. 

</TEXT>

