<F P=101> HONDURAS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reina Calls for Examining Existence of Palmerola Base From `Another Context' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1802211394 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 1902 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1802211394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text]Tegucigalpa, 18 Feb (DPA) -- The presence of foreign 
troops in Honduras for military purposes "no longer makes any 
sense" now that the Cold War is over, says Honduran President 
Carlos Roberto Reina Idiaquez. 
  The president said this in reference to the existence in 
Honduras of the U.S. military base at Palmerola in the central 
Department of Comayagua, approximately 80 km from Tegucigalpa. 
  The air force base was installed at the beginning of the 
eighties and was used by the United States to support the 
Nicaraguan contras who were fighting against the Sandinist 
government and the Salvadoran Government which was fighting 
against the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front. 
  At present the U.S. Government is still conducting 
operations 
at the base with 1,200 troops, and the base also houses the 
Honduran Military Aviation Academy. 
  Reina Idiaquez said he is examining the existence of the 
Palmerola base from "another context" and hinted that he would 
like the antinarcotics forces to be more active. 
  Honduras has proposed to Washington that it convert 
Palmerola 
into the Central American headquarters of the U.S. Drug 
Enforcement Administration (DEA). The United States already has 
two radars with which it monitors the flights and boats of South 
American drug traffickers who take advantage of the extensive 
aerial and maritime space of the Honduran Atlantic. 
  The Honduran president made the comment after a meeting 
today 
at the Government House with activists from the ruling Liberal 
Party when one of the participants asked him why he does not 
charge for the presence of foreign troops and use the money to 
amortize Honduras' foreign debt. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

