<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Teachers, Parents Warned of LSD Being Offered to High School Students </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WB0025A Mexico City EXCELSIOR in Spanish 2 Feb 94 STATES 
Section pp 1, 3 </F>

<F P=103> 94WB0025A </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City EXCELSIOR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by correspondent Rocio Galvan] </F>
  [Text] Tijuana, Baja California, 1 February--The local 
agency of the Office of the Attorney General of the Republic 
[PGR] warned teachers and parents of the presence of stickers 
impregnated with drugs and poison being offered to students. 
This announcement was made today by the head of that office, 
Arturo Ochoa Palacios. 
  He indicated that the illustrated stickers known as "Blue 
Star," pieces of paper with a blue star, were analyzed, and 
discovered to be saturated with drugs and poison. 
  He explained that they are the size of a pencil eraser, and 
that each star is permeated with lysergic acid (LSD); although 
others contain one of the most deadly poisons, strychnine. 
  The purpose of the distribution of these items among 
secondary school students is still unknown. Nevertheless, 
according to the official, "The information being given to 
students and teachers has been intensified, and flyers are being 
disseminated as well, to warn all educational establishments." 
  He noted that some teachers have notified the PGR 
authorities 
that the stickers are also being sold as tattoos, appearing on 
brightly colored paper and resembling postage stamps, with 
sketches of cartoon characters. 
  These stickers have been distributed wrapped in a fine metal 
sheet and, he added, constitute a new method of selling drugs to 
children and adolescents. 
  He said that teachers have also reported symptoms caused by 
contact with these substances, such as hallucinations, intense 
vomiting, uncontrolled laughter, mood swings, and body 
temperature changes. 
  Admitting that the distribution center is unknown, as is the 
length of time that these stickers have been circulating in Baja 
California, he concluded by saying: "The most important thing, 
however, is to advise parents and teachers to take precautions." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

