<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> PANAMA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government `Strongly Rejects' Charges of `Lack of Effort' To Stem Money Laundering </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1202013594 Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 
2300 GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1202013594 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City Circuito RPC Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "RPC Television News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Panamanian Government strongly rejects 
statements made by U.S. State Department official Robert Gelbard 
on drug money laundering. 
  A Foreign Ministry communique sent to the U.S. ambassador in 
Panama states that charges by the previously mentioned official 
are false, as Panama has undertaken serious and decisive actions 
to fight drug trafficking and money laundering since 1990. 
  The document, which lists in 12 points everything Panama has 
done to stamp out these crimes, says it is unacceptable for the 
United States to express criticism which does not seriously 
reflect the real position and will of the Panamanian Government. 
  Furthermore, the communique questions the U.S. Senate's 
delay 
in ratifying the Mutual Legal Assistance Treaty [MLAT] for 
criminal affairs, which has already been approved by the 
Republic of Panama. 
  The Panamanian Foreign Ministry communique responds to 
statements made by Gelbard, who harshly attacked the Panamanian 
Government for what he called a lack of effort in fighting money 
laundering. 
  The State Department official's statements could stop Panama 
from achieving MLAT certification and from obtaining loans from 
Congress for the eradication of drug trafficking. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

