<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> PARAGUAY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ambassador Says Country Would `Benefit' From American Troop Presence </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1602165794 Asuncion ULTIMA HORA in Spanish 14 Feb 94 p 24 </F>
<F P=103> PY1602165794 </F>
<F P=104>  Asuncion ULTIMA HORA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Juan Esteban Aguirre, Paraguayan ambassador </F>
to the United States, by reporter Andres Dario Cardozo 
Hohn--place and date not given] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Cardozo] Ambassador Aguirre, 
it would seem that the United States still distrusts us as far 
as drug trafficking is concerned. 
  [Aguirre] The United States has given top priority to the 
drug problem. We need a precise diagnosis of drug trafficking 
in Paraguay. There is a problem and we need to know how bad it 
is to be able to implement the appropriate corrective measures. 
  I believe that at present we do not have the diagnosis of 
the 
situation that we need. 
  As to the request to allow U.S. troops into Paraguay, I do 
not believe it has anything to do with drug trafficking. I do 
not believe the U.S. military is coming to fight drug 
trafficking in Paraguay. As far as I am concerned, the two 
issues are not connected because we handle drug trafficking at 
another level, working with the United States through the 
National Antidrug Secretariat (Senad). 
  [Cardozo] Then what would be the point of these troops 
coming 
to Paraguay? 
  [Aguirre] I believe the United States looks for friendly, 
safe countries to train their troops. 
  If we bear in mind the role the United States plays in the 
world, where they deploy and use their Armed Forces to resolve 
problems, we will realize that there are few places in the world 
where they can send their soldiers without fear that they might 
be attacked. 
  [Cardozo] Would our country benefit from the presence of 
these soldiers? 
  [Aguirre] In addition to what they are promising to build, 
we 
also would benefit from being able to watch the deployment of 
the world's most advanced military technology. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-41342 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptdd008__l94050" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TDD-94-008-L </AU>
Document Type:JPRS 
Document Title:Narcotics 

<DATE1>  23 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> PERU </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fujimori Comments on U.S. Antidrug Efforts, Need To Shift Focus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1602005494 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2335 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1602005494 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 15 Feb (EFE) -- Peruvian 
President Alberto Fujimori said in Santa Fe de Bogota today that 
the U.S. counternarcotics struggle has proved useless although 
"billions of dollars were spent." "The change in the U.S. 
counternarcotics policy confirms that this policy did not yield 
the expected results." Although "billions of dollars were 
spent, nothing was attained," he said. 
  Fujimori made the remark in a news conference at the Narino 
Presidential Palace at the end of a two-day official visit. 
Fujimori said that, in view of the failure of the U.S. 
counternarcotics policy, the governments of the coca-producing 
countries, including Peru and Colombia, should outline joint 
strategies and insist that consumption is the reason for the 
persistence of drug trafficking. 
  According to Fujimori, "it is necessary to reassess" the 
alleged reduction in drug use, a crime "that has distorted our 
economies." He insisted that the problem "should be tackled by 
everyone involved" and that "imaginative solutions" should be 
sought. He said the war on drugs as it has been waged, "should 
not continue this way without offering alternatives to coca 
planters." He also said that his country cannot repress "200,000 
poor coca planters" without offering them other ways out. 
  He pointed out that drug trafficking must be attacked by 
"hitting the big ones, not the poor ones." He insisted that 
drug trafficking could end "when there is economic development." 
  The end of drug trafficking, without setting any deadlines, 
"does not depend on us, but on consumers," Fujimori concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

