<F P=101> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Announces Increase in Drug Seizures in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1402140994 Paris AFP in English 1306 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1402140994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Feb 14 (AFP) -- French drug seizures rose 
sharply in 1993 over the previous year with a 50 percent 
increase in the heroin haul, government spokesman Nicolas 
Sarkozy said on Monday. 
  Sarkozy, who is also budget minister, said a total of 40 
tonnes of drugs were seized in 1993, including 38 tonnes of 
cannabis resin, 1.28 tonnes of cocaine and more than 230 
kilograms (464.6 lbs) of heroin. 
  He added that the French customs had helped the customs 
services of several foreign countries to seize more than 33 
tonnes of drugs "through intensive exchange of information and 
coordinated operations." 
  The minister said it was difficult to tell if the customs 
service was working more efficiently or whether there had been a 
rise in drug smuggling. "In any case, this demonstrates an 
extremely preoccupying situation," Sarkozy said. 

</TEXT>

