<H3> <TI>   Health Minister Discloses Statistics on Drug Addiction in Dublin Area </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WD0210A Dublin IRISH INDEPENDENT in English 17 Dec 93 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> 94WD0210A </F>
<F P=104>  Dublin IRISH INDEPENDENT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Mairtin MacCormaic: "5,000 in Capital on Hard </F>
Drugs"] 
  [Text] Some 5,000 people in the Dublin area are now 
addicted to hard drugs such as heroin, Health Minister Brendan 
Howlin disclosed in the Dail yesterday. 
  And he admitted in reply to questions from Independent TD 
Tony Gregory that the figure could be as high as 7,000. 
  "However, it's estimated that--excluding persons attending 
the community services established by the Eastern Health 
Board--approximately 1,850 persons are receiving treatment for 
drug abuse in various treatment centres." 
  A total 352 people are on the methadone and maintenance 
programmes in the satellite clinics and a number of others are 
receiving treatment from general practitioners. 
  The services now in place and those being developed have 
been 
introduced as a result of the strategies prepared by the 
National Co-ordinating Committee on Drug Abuse and the National 
AIDS Strategy Committee, explained the Minister. 
  And he told the TD: "The deputy can be assured I regard this 
area as a priority and have made provision in the 1994 estimates 
to develop these services further." 
  Mr Gregory said that in spite of very dedicated staff the 
satellite clinics provided "little more than a Band Aid service." 
  In some instances two counsellors were looking after in 
excess of 100 addicts, and a waiting list of nearly 200 others. 

</TEXT>

